      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":24,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 3-minute brisk walk to ease into the effort. Let your breathing settle before you begin running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":18,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences. This is pure aerobic base-building — resist the urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Slow to a brisk walk for the final 3 minutes. Focus on deep, relaxed breathing.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 3-minute brisk walk before easing into your easy running pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes post-run and spend 5 minutes doing gentle leg swings, calf stretches, and hip flexor stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run for the week. At your current base, consistency matters far more than intensity. Running at 7:00–8:00 /km builds your aerobic engine — the cardiovascular and muscular infrastructure that everything else sits on top of. Keep it genuinely easy; if you feel like you're working hard, slow down.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Run-Walk Intervals — Building Stamina\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":420,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute brisk walk to warm up the legs and get the heart rate moving gradually.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":435,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"Alternate 4 minutes of easy running with 1 minute of walking, repeated 4 times. This builds time on feet without over-stressing your system. Focus on smooth, relaxed form during the running portions.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy walk or very slow jog to bring your heart rate down comfortably.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 3-minute brisk walk. Do a few ankle circles and leg swings before starting the intervals.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5–7 minutes post-run. Stretch your calves, hamstrings, and hip flexors — hold each for 20–30 seconds.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This mid-week session uses a run-walk format to gently increase your time on feet. Run-walk training is a legitimate and evidence-based method used by coaches at every level — it protects your tendons and joints while still building aerobic fitness. The goal here is accumulating quality aerobic minutes, not speed. Over the coming weeks, the walking breaks will gradually shorten.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run — Easy & Steady\",\"target_distance_km\":5,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":480,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":480,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":500,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 4-minute walk, then ease into a slow jog. Let the first few minutes feel almost too easy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at the slower end of your easy pace — aim for 8:00 /km or even a touch slower. The long run is about time on feet, not distance covered quickly. Walk breaks are completely fine and encouraged if needed.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":500,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 4 minutes. This is part of the workout, not an afterthought — it helps flush lactate and signals recovery to your body.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 4 minutes before starting. Hydrate before you head out — even for a 40-minute run, starting well-hydrated makes a real difference.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 4 minutes, then spend 8–10 minutes stretching: calf raises and stretches, hamstring stretch, quad stretch, and hip flexor lunge. This is your most important recovery window of the week.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your Saturday long run is the cornerstone of your week. At 5 km, it matches your current long run distance — we're not adding volume yet, just establishing the habit and making sure the effort is genuinely easy. The physiological purpose is building mitochondrial density and teaching your body to use fat as fuel. Both adaptations take time and require staying at a low intensity. Slower is better here.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
